what is a `maintainer merge` and given that the bot says it is already on some merge queue, I am not sure how I wait for CI.

@Shreyas4991 a `maintainer merge` is when a [reviewer](https://leanprover-community.github.io/teams/reviewers.html) places a PR on a queue (really just a thread in a private channel on Zulip) for a maintainer to look at and potentially merge. Sometimes maintainers themselves use this queue so that they can get approval from another maintainer, as I have done here. You can still wait for CI as normal, but unlike delegation, a `maintainer merge` does not give anyone the authority to merge (other than maintainers themselves, but they already had such authority). Note: my reference to CI was for the maintainer so that they didn't think it was already fully prepared for merging.

```suggestion
`nth_rw n [eq‚ÇÅ, eq‚ÇÇ,...]` rewrites the `n`·µó ∞ occurrence of each equality `eq‚ÇÅ`, `eq‚ÇÇ`,... etc.
```
to match your other docstring.

```suggestion
to be rewritten. `nth_rewrite n [eq‚ÇÅ, eq‚ÇÇ, ..., eq‚Çò]` will rewrite the `n`·µó ∞ occurrence
of each of the `m` equalities `eq·µ¢`.
```
(which is a bit like what the `simp` docstring uses)

```suggestion
Note: The occurrences are counted beginning with `1` and not `0`, this is different than in
```

```suggestion
as an _occurrence_ of `t` for all subsequent rewrites of `t` with `eq‚±º` for `j > i`.
```
You already have a mention of the the `rfl` in the first line; I don't think it's worth mentioning twice
I think a bit of redundancy is better since the docstring is not a one-liner.
I added some examples which added lines to the docstring. So the redundancy helps even more.
I think I rather agree with Ruben here, but I guess that doesn't really matter either.
I think (in both of these) I'd put a paragraph break before explaining how the tactic works with multiple lemmas, since that's a pretty obscure feature
I added them and also some examples.
(this is resolved, I believe)

I would suggest to `import Mathlib.Tactic.ExtendDoc` and then use `@[inherit_doc nthRewriteSeq]` on the`nth_rw` macro along with the something like the following just below it:

```
extend_docs nthRwSeq before
  "`nth_rw` is like `nth_rewrite`, but also tries to close the goal by trying `rfl` afterwards.
  "
```
That way you could avoid writing that much documentation twice. The user will first see the sentense about `nth_rw` being essentially `nth_rewrite` followed by the doc for the latter.
That sounds nice, but it doesn't adapt the examples very well. I was hoping the documentation could be entirely self-contained.

I have to admit, I didn't even read the second docstring. If it is merely a `nth_rewrite --> nth_rw` renaming, I think this suggestion would make a lot of sense and wouldn't be confusing for the reader. And it would simplify maintainability (e.g. I think the last example of the second docstring is already out-of-sync again)

However, if there is more change to it might not be ideal.

Anyways, this is a completely _optional_ suggestion!

The doc-string for `nth_rw` is not really separately helpful from the doc-string for `nth_rewrite`: it's not like it exhibits the difference in behaviour between the two. To be honest I think it would be fine to just cross-reference to from `nth_rewrite` to `nth_rw`. (On the principle that `nth_rw` will be used 10x more often, so put the detailed examples there.)

Even better, just have a single doc-string, copied via `inherit_doc` that explains both together. e.g.

`nth_rw` and `nth_rewrite` are analogues of `rw` and `rewrite` that allow restricting which occurrence of a patttern to replace. `nth_rw` tries to close the goal after rewriting with a reducible transparency `rfl`, while `nth_rewrite` does not (just as for `rw` and `rewrite`).

.... now continue with examples just in terms of `nth_rw`.

The issue is the vscode doc tooltip only shows you the docstring for the tactic your mouse pointer is hovering on. So if I am hovering on nth_rw, I would like to see a full explanation rather than being redirected to nth_rewrite or vice versa

If inherit doc could accept parameters and format strings, then the docstrings of nth_rw would be correct, especially the examples. My rule of thumb for documentation examples is that they should be copy pastable with minimum modification.

I think now that we have the customized docstrings, the question is whether they will be diverging, so that one is updated and the other isn't. That's potentially more harm than copypastability breaking. My estimate is that we'll be okay with two similar docstrings, so I'm inclined to keep these as-is.
Kim  has reacted with a (y) to @Vierkantor 's suggestion to keep these strings as is. Shall I assume that this can be marked resolved?

```suggestion
of each of the `m` equalities `eq·µ¢`in that order. Occurrences are counted beginning with `1`.
For example,
```
(sentence appears twice)

"from the left" is not 100% correct in my opinion, maybe you could also add the following example to explain why it is the 2nd occurence and not the 1st:

```
example (a b c : Nat) : (a + b) + c = (b + a) + c := by
  nth_rewrite 2 [Nat.add_comm]
  rfl
```
Ah yes, this is true. Technically `nth_rewrite` looks at expression trees. I am not sure how convey this intuitively without referring to the expression tree idea.
Fixed it with `order of precedence` and added your example to explain the importance of order of precedence.

This part I find quite hard to read, and I do find this behaviour intuitive as is, not requiring much explanation.

Maybe this entire paragraph could be shortened to something like the following?

> `nth_rewrite` with multiple arguments recalculates the occurences after each step newly, so for `(h : a = a + b)`, `nth_rewrite 3 [h, h]` changes `a + a + a + a + a = 0` to `a + a + (a + b) + a + a = 0` in the first step and then to `a + a + ((a + b) + b) + a + a = 0` in the second.

In a previous iteration I had such a short sentence. The problem is if someone is not comfortable with binder substitution and name capture issues, then it is a bit hard for them to see what is happening without a detailed example. I completely expect the "recalculates the occurrences after each step newly" part to confuse them. That is why I split that into many sentences and detailed proofs state examples.
Fair enough. I also think the new iteration with the goal states is good.

```suggestion
‚ä¢ a + a + (a + b + b) + a + a = 0
```
Isn't it?
No this is the proof state after the first rewrite.
I think the remaining question from Zulip is whether you want to remove this. I personally think it's perferctly fine to drop it. Also a completely _optional_ suggestion.
I think we should drop the last paragraph. No need to remind users of Lean 3 behavior a year past the completion of the port.

I think users will be much more familiar with `rw` than `nth_rewrite`, so I would rephrase in terms of `rw`.
```suggestion
`nth_rw` is a variant of `rw` that only changes the `n`·µó ∞ _occurrence_ of the expression to be
rewritten. Like `rw`, unlike `nth_rewrite` it will try to close the goal by trying `rfl` afterwards.
```
This is a very good idea. I'll add it in right away.
